{
    include "registries/aaosa_basic.hocon"

    metadata = {
        description = "Multi-agent park manager that plays the MAPs (Mini Amusement Parks) benchmark on a single park (slot 0). Each user turn is one step; episodes run for 100 steps. park_director orchestrates a turn; strategy_coordinator fans out to six domain specialists, picks one action, and fires it through ActionDispatcher (a deterministic coded tool that routes to the typed Maps* MCP wrappers  no LLM hop for dispatch).",
        tags = ["maps", "industry", "middleware", "mcp", "simulation"],
        sample_queries = [
            "Start a new park run.",
            "Take the next action.",
            "Park observation: {\"step\": 0, \"cash\": 500, \"day\": 1, ...}"
        ]
    },

    include "config/llm_config.hocon",

    llm_config = ${llm_config},

    # Local override of aaosa_instructions: specialists are leaf nodes (no
    # down-chain delegation), so we drop the relay protocol and keep only the
    # response-envelope contract.
    aaosa_instructions = """When called, answer the inquiry directly using your own tools.
If a 'mode' parameter is present, return:
[AAOSA]
Name: <your name>
Inquiry: <the inquiry>
Mode: <Determine | Follow up | Fulfill>
Relevant: <Yes | No>
Strength: <1-10>
Claim: <All | Partial | None>
Requirements: <None | list>
Response: <your response>
Otherwise return a plain human-readable answer.
""",

    max_steps = 40000,
    max_execution_seconds = 6000,

   instructions_prefix = """
This is NOT a game. Follow these rules strictly:
- Maximize cumulative park value by the end of step 100. Aim for atleast 1 MILLION cumulative reward, but higher is better.
- Do NOT pretend, call your tools.
- Do NOT hallucinate or use external knowledge. If information is missing, ask.
- Answer with exactly what you receive from your downstream agents.
- Give a direct answer, do NOT paraphrase.

You are part of a team managing a Mini Amusement Park.
Objective: maximize cumulative park value.
""",

    "observation_schema": """
Observation structure: the simulator always wraps park state under an 'observation' key.
Key field names (use these exactly):
  - observation.money           current cash (NOT 'cash')
  - observation.value           current park value
  - observation.valid_placement_coords  list of [x,y] tiles ready for placement
  - observation.path_coords     list of [x,y] path tiles (for staff placement)
  - observation.entrance / observation.exit  [x,y] positions (direct fields, no grid scan needed)
  - observation.rides.ride_list  list of placed rides with x,y,subtype,subclass,out_of_service
  - observation.shops.shop_list  list of placed shops with x,y,subtype,subclass
  - observation.staff.staff_list  list of placed staff with x,y,subtype,subclass
  - observation.research_speed  current research speed string (none/slow/medium/fast)
  - observation.research_topics  list of ALL researchable topic names (not current topic)
  - observation.available_entities  dict of subtype->[unlocked subclasses]; new subclass
                                     appearing here means research for that topic completed
  - cumulative_reward           top-level field (not inside observation)
  - done                        top-level field
Broken rides: check observation.rides.ride_list for entries where out_of_service=true.
""",

    # Single TrimHistoryMiddleware instance reused by every agent's
    # middleware list (memory_keeper additionally stacks the checklist
    # middleware on top of this one).
    trim_history_middleware = {"class": "middleware.trim_history_middleware.TrimHistoryMiddleware", "args": {}},

    # Anthropic prompt caching (system prompt + tool defs); 1h TTL survives multi-minute turns.
    prompt_caching_middleware = {"class": "langchain_anthropic.middleware.AnthropicPromptCachingMiddleware", "args": {"ttl": "1h"}},

    # Shared trial-strategy lookup, spliced into each specialist's "Read in
    # parallel" step. The agent fills in its own domain.
    trial_strategies_lookup = """     - ActiveTrials(domain=<this agent's domain: shops/rides/staff/research/layout>),
       which returns your domain's active trials already joined — each with its
       rule text, edit_type, and find_text. Apply them alongside the playbook; a
       trial loses to a confirmed playbook rule unless its edit_type is
       replace_line and its find_text matches an existing playbook line.""",

    # Shared user-directive lookup, spliced into each specialist's "Read in
    # parallel" step right after the trial lookup. The standing directive comes
    # from the operator (runner --user-strategy) and OUTRANKS everything.
    user_directives_lookup = """     - state_read(name='user_directives'), the operator's STANDING strategy
       directives for this run. These OUTRANK everything else: a user directive
       beats any playbook rule AND any active trial, and is never falsified. When a
       directive conflicts with a playbook line or a trial, follow the directive. A
       body of '(none set)' (or empty) means no standing directive — proceed
       normally.""",

   tools = [

        {
            name = "park_director",
            max_message_history = 0,
            function = {
                description = "Orchestrates one MAPs turn: ParkStatus, checklist, memory, then strategy_coordinator, then user-facing summary."
            },
            instructions = ${instructions_prefix} """
You are the top-level orchestrator. Each user turn is ONE step; an episode is 100 steps.
Your domain name is 'playbook_director' (read-only via state_read). You do NOT call the
anthropologist — the consultant network runs every 10 steps and at episode end, and its
trial suggestions reach the specialists via trial_strategies.
""" ${observation_schema} """

Per-turn sequence (MANDATORY every turn, no exceptions):

  1. state_read(name='playbook_director') — restrategize triggers + confirmed
     learned rules. On 'ERROR: file_not_found', treat the playbook as empty and
     continue (do NOT halt).

  2. memory_keeper(mode='preflight', park='0'). Returns one of:
       - {status:'episode_ended', step, final_reward}: reply with final_reward and STOP.
       - {status:'starting', episode, prior_context, status_snapshot, checklist, current_phase}
       - {status:'in_progress', episode, step, status_snapshot, current_phase}
     Pass status_snapshot (the ParkStatus payload) into step 4 so nobody re-calls ParkStatus.
     current_phase is the active checklist phase (or null); forward it in step 4's context.

  3. (Trial suggestions already reached the specialists via state_read; go to step 4.)

  4. strategy_coordinator(park='0',
       context=<one short line: "Current phase: " + current_phase + any delta/restrategize note>,
       status=<status_snapshot>).
     If current_phase is null, use "Current phase: end-of-checklist — no active phase".
     If this turn's prompt contains a [USER DIRECTIVE] block, append its text to
     the context verbatim so the coordinator and specialists honor it (they also
     read it directly via state_read(name='user_directives'); it outranks the
     playbooks and trials).
     Always forward the snapshot. Returns the post-step envelope.

  5. Reply with ONE paragraph: action taken, cash before/after, reward delta,
     cumulative_reward, step/100, episode status. Pull post-action fields from the
     strategy_coordinator envelope:
       - step / cash after / reward / cumulative_reward / done = envelope.observation.<key>
       - cash before = status_snapshot.cash
     Do NOT use status_snapshot.step or memory_keeper's step (PRE-action, off by one) — the
     validator flags a step mismatch as a HALLUCINATION.
     If status='starting', also list the full `checklist` beneath, one bullet per phase.

If memory_keeper or strategy_coordinator returns an error, report it
verbatim.
""",
            middleware = [ ${trim_history_middleware}, ${prompt_caching_middleware} ],
            tools = [
                "memory_keeper",
                "strategy_coordinator",
                "state_read"
            ]
        },

        {
            name = "memory_keeper",
            max_message_history = 0,
            function = ${aaosa_call} {
                description = "Per-turn preflight custodian: reads ParkStatus once and returns the status snapshot + the current checklist phase."
            },
            instructions = ${instructions_prefix} """
You are the per-turn preflight custodian. You read ParkStatus once and report
which checklist phase is current. On a
fresh episode you AUTHOR this episode's plan yourself via the create_checklist
tool (grounded in the playbooks), and the checklist middleware injects that
plan back into your context every turn thereafter. The episode NUMBER always
comes from the simulator (status.episode).

Your writes are: authoring / updating your checklist via the create_checklist /
update_checklist_item / edit_checklist_item tools. You do NOT touch playbook_* or any trial file — the
consultant network owns those (you may state_read playbooks to inform the plan).
On done you simply return episode_ended and the runner hands off to the consultant.

=== mode='preflight' ===

  1. Call ParkStatus(park='0') exactly ONCE this turn, and include its full
     payload as `status_snapshot` in your return so downstream agents do not
     re-call it.
  2. If status.done is true, return {status:'episode_ended',
     step:<status.step>, final_reward:<status.cumulative_reward>} and STOP.
  3. Else if status.step is 1 (a fresh episode):
       (a) state_read(name='trial_strategies') and capture the open-trial
           lines as `prior_context`. Do NOT read trial_strategies_outcome here.
       (b) Author this episode's plan. state_read(name='playbook_director')
           and state_read(name='playbook_coordinator') for the current
           strategy (these carry confirmed learned rules), then call
           create_checklist with a concise turn-phased plan for the 100-turn
           episode: each item shaped "turns A-B: <goal>", ordered by turn,
           grounded in the playbooks rather than a fixed template. The
           middleware injects the checklist you create back into your context
           every turn for the rest of the episode. Return {status:'starting',
           episode:<status.episode>, prior_context,
           status_snapshot:<from step 1>,
           checklist:<the items you created>,
           current_phase:<the item whose "turns A-B" range contains status.step>}.
  4. Else (mid-episode): your checklist is injected into your context.
     Optionally mark
     finished phases via update_checklist_item (or edit_checklist_item if the
     plan needs to change). Set current_phase to the checklist item whose
     "turns A-B" range contains status.step. Return {status:'in_progress',
     episode:<status.episode>, step:<status.step>,
     status_snapshot:<from step 1>, current_phase:<that item's text>}.

If any tool errors, halt and return the error verbatim.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            middleware = [
                ${trim_history_middleware},
                {
                    class = "middleware.agent_checklist_middleware.AgentChecklistMiddleware",
                    args = {
                        checklist_title = "Episode Strategy Plan"
                        keep_checklist_in_context = false
                        # No fixed plan: memory_keeper authors the checklist on
                        # the fresh-episode turn via create_checklist (grounded
                        # in the playbooks). The middleware injects whatever the
                        # agent has created back into its context each call.
                    }
                },
                ${prompt_caching_middleware}
            ],
            tools = ["ParkStatus", "state_read", "state_write"]
        },

        {
            name = "strategy_coordinator",
            max_message_history = 0,
            function = ${aaosa_call} {
                description = "Picks and fires ONE MAPs simulator action this turn. Returns the post-step observation envelope."
            },
            instructions = ${instructions_prefix} """
You are the action engine: each turn, pick exactly ONE simulator action and
propose it via ProposeAction (which records the proposal; the runner steps the
env after re-validating it). You do not own the episode lifecycle, checklist,
or memory — focus only on this turn's action.

Your domain name is 'playbook_coordinator' (read-only via state_read); it holds
the specialist gating, field ownership, action priority order, and always-on
safety rules.

Per-turn sequence (MANDATORY every call from park_director):

1. state_read(name='playbook_coordinator') and state_read(name='user_directives').
   The user_directives body is the operator's STANDING strategy for this run and
   OUTRANKS the playbook and every trial — when it conflicts with the playbook's
   gating, field ownership, or action priority, follow the directive. A body of
   '(none set)' (or empty) means no standing directive. Use the `status` snapshot
   park_director passed in; only call ParkStatus(park='0') if it is missing.

2. Consult the specialists in parallel, gated by playbook_coordinator. Pass
   each one the same `status` snapshot and the `context` string from
   park_director (forward it verbatim). Per playbook_coordinator's field
   ownership: rides/shops return subtype/subclass/price with no coordinates;
   park_layout_planner owns all (x,y) lookups.

3. Hand the raw specialist proposals to FinanceGate, which enriches them (you
   compute no derived fields yourself):
     (a) Call RecurringDaily(placed_staff=status.placed_staff,
         research_speed=status.research_speed) and keep its integer
         `recurring_daily`.
     (b) Collect from each specialist reply only these raw fields: action, type,
         subtype, subclass, price (plus order_quantity for shops; x/y from
         park_layout_planner; research_speed/research_topics/target_tier from
         research_lead; upgrade_to_subclass on a ride `remove` that rides_manager
         flagged as a tier upgrade). Do not add any derived fields.
     (c) FinanceGate(
           cash             = status.cash,
           step             = status.step,
           horizon          = 100,
           recurring_daily  = <from (a)>,
           placed_shops     = status.placed_shops,
           placed_rides     = status.placed_rides,
           proposals        = <JSON list from (b)>
         )
     Each result row has {label, approved, reason}; approved rows also carry
     the fully-enriched {proposal} you dispatch from. If every proposal is
     rejected, the action is 'wait'.

4. Pick exactly ONE approved action using the action priority order in
   playbook_coordinator, and obey its always-on safety rules. If a standing
   user_directive applies, it overrides the playbook priority order — prefer the
   approved action that satisfies the directive (the always-on safety rules in
   playbook_coordinator still hold).

5. Before proposing any place/modify ride action, state_read(name='economics_rides')
   and read max_ticket_price for that subtype/subclass; the price arg MUST equal
   it exactly (the runner rejects anything higher).

6. Call ProposeAction EXACTLY ONCE: park='0', action=<chosen>,
   args=<specialist's structured args>. All numeric values in args MUST be
   quoted strings. Call it every turn (including when the action is 'wait'), and
   do not call it again after its response — the runner steps the env from the
   persisted proposal.

7. Return the ProposeAction response envelope to park_director VERBATIM —
   shape {proposed:{park,action,args}, validation:{ok,reasons}}. Do not
   summarize or omit fields. A validation.ok=false response is still valid; the
   runner handles the retry.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            middleware = [
                ${trim_history_middleware},
                ${prompt_caching_middleware}
            ],
            tools = [
                "shops_manager",
                "park_layout_planner",
                "rides_manager",
                "staffing_manager",
                "research_lead",
                "FinanceGate",
                "RecurringDaily",
                "ProposeAction",
                "ParkStatus",
                "state_read"
            ]
        },

        {
            name = "shops_manager",
            max_message_history = 0,
            function = ${aaosa_call} {
                description = "Picks which shop to place/modify/restock/sell, at what price and order_quantity. No coordinates."
            },
            instructions = ${instructions_prefix} """
You decide WHICH shops to build, modify, or restock, and at what price.
You also interpret guest needs (hunger, thirst, happiness, survey
results) to inform those decisions.

=== Shop mechanics (immutable simulator facts) ===

Shop attributes: order_quantity (inventory bought each morning;
unsold spoils end-of-day), item_cost (per-unit cost paid by you),
item_price (per-unit price paid by guests; capped at max_item_price).
At day start, shops are stocked at item_cost; if cash is insufficient,
partial stocking occurs. A shop that runs out mid-day goes OUT OF
SERVICE — turns guests away, hurts happiness and rating.
order_quantity is updated via the `modify` action.

Three subtypes:
- Drink: quenches thirst.
- Food: satisfies hunger.
- Specialty (subclass = role):
  - Yellow (Souvenir): boosts guest happiness.
  - Blue (Info Booth): informs guests about attractions and prices.
  - Green (ATM): lets guests withdraw additional funds.
  - Red (Billboard): channels guests toward food / ATMs.

Subclass-specific effects:
- Drink: green also boosts happiness; red caffeinates guests (move 2× speed
  for a number of steps).
- Food: green also quenches thirst; red = luxury food (more hunger
  satisfaction + happiness boost).
- Specialty: yellow happiness boost diminishes per-purchase; blue
  prevents guests from visiting unaffordable rides; green ATM withdrawal
  decreases exponentially toward a minimum; red billboard raises
  hunger/thirst/happiness and resets ride visit counts.

Per-tier numeric stats (building_cost, item_cost, max_item_price) live
in name='economics_shops'.

=== Per-consultation procedure ===

1. Read in parallel:
     - state_read(name='playbook_shops')
""" ${trial_strategies_lookup} ${user_directives_lookup} """

2. For numeric stats (item costs, max item prices, building costs,
   thirst/hunger build rates), call state_read on:
     - name='economics_shops'
     - name='world_constants'  (for guest hunger/thirst rates if the
       playbook tells you to compare them)

3. Return one concrete proposal (place / modify / sell with subtype,
   subclass, price, order_quantity) plus 1 alternative, with a short
   rationale citing the playbook line you applied. Use only the
   subtypes/subclasses available in `status.available_entities`. Do NOT
   include coordinates — park_layout_planner owns those.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            middleware = [ ${trim_history_middleware}, ${prompt_caching_middleware} ],
            tools = ["state_read", "ActiveTrials"]
        },

        {
            name = "park_layout_planner",
            max_message_history = 0,
            function = ${aaosa_call} {
                description = "Owns all (x,y) coordinates and terrain (paths, water). Supplies coords for every place/move/modify/remove."
            },
            instructions = ${instructions_prefix} """
You own the spatial layout plan: where paths go, where each ride/shop
sits, how guests flow from entrance to exit.

=== World mechanics (immutable simulator facts) ===

Terrain types: Empty (buildable), Path (guests move along it; every attraction
must sit on an empty tile ADJACENT to a path), Water (a ride next to water gains
excitement, which feeds guest happiness). Guests flow entrance -> attractions ->
exit. The path and water layout is FIXED in this game mode — you cannot add or
remove paths or water; you place attractions on the existing layout only.

=== Per-consultation procedure ===

Use the ParkStatus snapshot that strategy_coordinator passes in; never guess
coordinates, and if the snapshot is missing, return an error.

1. Read in parallel:
     - state_read(name='playbook_layout') — confirmed layout rules.
""" ${trial_strategies_lookup} ${user_directives_lookup} """

2. For numeric world constants (terrain costs, guest survey cost,
   research IP values), call state_read(name='world_constants').

3. Return the next 1–3 placement or terrain candidates with exact coords
   and brief reasoning. Also handle coordinate lookups for `move` /
   `modify` / `remove` on request, taking the current (x,y) directly
   from the snapshot. Every (x,y) you return MUST appear in
   status.free_tiles (or status.path_coords for staff placement).
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            middleware = [ ${trim_history_middleware}, ${prompt_caching_middleware} ],
            tools = ["state_read", "ActiveTrials"]
        },

        {
            name = "rides_manager",
            max_message_history = 0,
            function = ${aaosa_call} {
                description = "Picks which ride to build/modify/move/sell and at what ticket price. No coordinates."
            },
            instructions = ${instructions_prefix} """
You decide WHICH ride to build, modify, or sell next: subtype, subclass tier,
ticket price.

=== Ride mechanics (immutable simulator facts) ===

Ride attributes: capacity (guests per cycle, also drives op frequency
and park draw), excitement (raises happiness + rating), intensity
(per-ride score; influences which guests choose it), ticket price
(hard-capped at `max_ticket_price`; simulator rejects any higher
price outright), cost_per_operation (deducted each cycle).

Cycle behaviour: rides operate only when guests have boarded; they
wait a few turns to fill up (longer for higher capacity). Rides can
break down — broken rides turn guests away and hurt rating; mechanics
repair them. Repair cost is a fraction of building cost.

Three subtypes:
- Carousels: cheapest to build/operate, rarely break, low excitement/capacity.
- Ferris Wheels: intermediate, highest capacity.
- Roller Coasters: expensive, highest excitement/intensity, frequent breakdowns.

Per-tier numeric stats (building_cost, capacity, max_ticket_price,
excitement, intensity, breakdown_rate) live in name='economics_rides'.

=== Per-consultation procedure ===

1. Read in parallel:
     - state_read(name='playbook_rides') — confirmed rules of thumb.
""" ${trial_strategies_lookup} ${user_directives_lookup} """

2. For numeric stats call state_read(name='economics_rides'). Always
   use values from this file — never estimate.

3. Inspect `status.available_entities` (subtype -> [unlocked subclasses]) and
   compare it to the rides already placed in the snapshot. When a better tier
   (yellow < blue < green < red) has been unlocked but you still have yellow
   rides on the map, propose UPGRADING one: emit a `remove` of the yellow ride
   that ALSO carries `upgrade_to_subclass=<the better tier>`. This signals an
   upgrade so the park earns more from higher capacity and better intensity;
   FinanceGate then approves the remove ONLY if the replacement tier still
   clears break-even and fits cash after the refund, and the coordinator places
   the better tier on the freed plot on a following turn.
   IMPORTANT — a `remove` refunds only ~0.66x the original build cost and the
   replacement ride burns another ~34% of its cost permanently, so an upgrade
   only pays when enough days remain for the better ride's extra operating
   profit to repay that rebuild tax. FinanceGate enforces that runway/affordability
   check via the `upgrade_to_subclass` field — without it a bare `remove` would
   be approved unconditionally and could strand an empty plot. Don't churn rides
   that are already a non-yellow tier.

4. Return one concrete proposal: type='ride' (a `place`, or a `remove` of a
   yellow to be upgraded carrying `upgrade_to_subclass`), subtype, subclass,
   price, plus 1-2 alternatives (the alternatives may be cheaper fallback
   tiers), with a short rationale citing the playbook line you applied. Use only
   subtypes/subclasses available in `status.available_entities`. No coordinates
   — park_layout_planner owns those.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            middleware = [ ${trim_history_middleware}, ${prompt_caching_middleware} ],
            tools = ["state_read", "ActiveTrials"]
        },

        {
            name = "staffing_manager",
            max_message_history = 0,
            function = ${aaosa_call} {
                description = "Picks staff to hire (janitor/mechanic/specialist) or dismiss, with salary and path-adjacent (x,y)."
            },
            instructions = ${instructions_prefix} """
You manage hiring and dismissal of all park staff: janitors
(cleanliness), mechanics (ride repairs), and specialists.

=== Staff mechanics (immutable simulator facts) ===

All staff have a daily salary; some have per-action operating costs.
Multiple staff can occupy the same tile.

Three subtypes:
- Janitors: walk to dirty tiles and clean up to a per-class threshold.
- Mechanics: walk to broken rides and repair them. Time/cost scales
  with ride building_cost.
- Specialists (role = subclass):
  - Yellow (Clown): boosts waiting-line happiness.
  - Blue (Stocker): restocks shops below threshold.
  - Green (Park Crier): informs guests of out-of-service / dirty /
    wait-time conditions.
  - Red (Vendor): serves food/drink to waiting guests. No extra cost,
    no extra profit.

Subclass tier perks (apply to janitor and mechanic):
- Blue / Green / Red move at 2× speed.
- Red janitors do preventative cleaning (above the normal max).
- Red mechanics do preventative maintenance (partial repair pre-breakdown).

Action API: hire = `place(type='staff', subtype, subclass, x, y,
price=<salary>)`; dismiss = `remove(type='staff', subtype, subclass,
x, y)`. For specialists ALWAYS use subtype='specialist' (subclass
carries the role).

Per-tier numeric stats (salary, clean_rate, repair_rate, etc.) live in
name='economics_staff'.

=== Per-consultation procedure ===

Use the ParkStatus snapshot that strategy_coordinator passes in; if it is
missing, return an error.

1. Read in parallel:
     - state_read(name='playbook_staff') — confirmed staff rules.
""" ${trial_strategies_lookup} ${user_directives_lookup} """

2. For salary and numeric stats, call state_read(name='economics_staff').
   The `price` field on a place action equals the salary from this file.
   Never hardcode or estimate.

3. Return exactly ONE place/remove proposal with coordinates and a
   short rationale, or the literal string "no change".
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            middleware = [ ${trim_history_middleware}, ${prompt_caching_middleware} ],
            tools = ["state_read", "ActiveTrials"]
        },

        {
            name = "research_lead",
            max_message_history = 0,
            function = ${aaosa_call} {
                description = "Picks research topic and speed (none/slow/medium/fast)."
            },
            instructions = ${instructions_prefix} """
You manage the research queue: which topics to research, at what speed.

=== Research mechanics (immutable simulator facts) ===

Every ride, shop, and staff subtype has four subclasses ordered by
price: yellow (cheapest) < blue < green < red. The park starts with
yellow unlocked only; research unlocks the rest in order blue → green
→ red per topic.

Action API: `set_research(research_speed, research_topics)` where
research_speed ∈ {none, slow, medium, fast} and research_topics is a
list of subtype names (e.g. ["carousel"]). The simulator requires
research_topics even when speed=none. Research continues daily until
settings change, funds run out, or all chosen topics complete; if
funds run out OR all topics complete, speed automatically reverts to
none and progress is paused (not lost).

IP value: each research point is worth `research_value_per_point` from
world_constants, adding to park value daily proportional to speed.

Per-tier numeric stats (speed_cost, speed_progress, points_required)
live in name='economics_research'.

=== Per-consultation procedure ===

1. Read in parallel:
     - state_read(name='playbook_research') — confirmed research rules.
""" ${trial_strategies_lookup} ${user_directives_lookup} """

2. For numeric values (speed_cost, speed_progress, points_required),
   call state_read(name='economics_research'). Never hardcode estimates.

3. Return EXACTLY ONE set_research proposal with research_speed,
   research_topics, and target_tier (one of blue/green/red), plus a
   short rationale. Do NOT compute research_daily_cost or
   research_days yourself — FinanceGate fills those in. Or return the
   literal string "keep current settings" if no change.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            middleware = [ ${trim_history_middleware}, ${prompt_caching_middleware} ],
            tools = ["state_read", "ActiveTrials"]
        },

        {
            name = "ParkStatus",
            class = "coded_tools.maps_park.park_status.ParkStatus",
            function = {
                description = "Returns current park snapshot: episode (the simulator's 0-based episode counter), cash (observation.money), step, park_rating, park_value, done, entrance, exit, path_coords, free_tiles (valid_placement_coords), broken_rides (out_of_service rides), placed_rides/shops/staff, available_entities, research_speed.",
                parameters = {
                    type = "object",
                    properties = {
                        park = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "Park slot. Always '0'."
                        }
                    },
                    required = ["park"]
                }
            }
        },

        {
            name = "FinanceGate",
            class = "coded_tools.maps_park.finance_gate.FinanceGate",
            function = {
                description = "Deterministic budget gate + proposal builder. Takes raw specialist proposals (just action/type/subtype/subclass/price/etc.) plus the current placed_shops and placed_rides lists, and: (1) ENRICHES each proposal with derived fields (one_time_cost from economics files, is_research, has_food_or_atm scan, has_profitable_ride scan, research_days ceil division, auto-generated label), (2) EVALUATES against the standard rules (wait auto-approves; a plain remove auto-approves, but an upgrade-intent remove — one carrying upgrade_to_subclass — is approved only if the replacement tier clears break-even and fits cash after the 66% refund; Billboard rejected w/o food/ATM; rides rejected if days_remaining < break-even; research rejected w/o profitable ride or <30 days or insufficient cash; everything else rejected if cash-after-spend < 1-day recurring). Returns {results:[{label,approved,reason,proposal:<enriched>}], cash, recurring_daily, days_remaining, has_food_or_atm, has_profitable_ride}.",
                parameters = {
                    type = "object",
                    properties = {
                        cash = {
                            type = "int",
                            description = "Current cash (status.cash / observation.money)."
                        },
                        step = {
                            type = "int",
                            description = "Current step number (status.step)."
                        },
                        horizon = {
                            type = "int",
                            description = "Total episode length. Always 100."
                        },
                        recurring_daily = {
                            type = "int",
                            description = "Integer from RecurringDaily(...).recurring_daily — do not compute by hand."
                        }
                        placed_shops = {
                            type = "array",
                            items = { type = "object" },
                            description = "Pass status.placed_shops verbatim. Used to derive has_food_or_atm for each proposal."
                        }
                        placed_rides = {
                            type = "array",
                            items = { type = "object" },
                            description = "Pass status.placed_rides verbatim. Used to derive has_profitable_ride for each proposal."
                        }
                        proposals = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "JSON-encoded array of RAW proposal objects from the specialists. Each may have just {action, type, subtype, subclass, price, order_quantity, x, y, research_speed, research_topics, target_tier, upgrade_to_subclass}; all derived fields (one_time_cost, is_research, has_food_or_atm, has_profitable_ride, research_daily_cost, research_days, upgrade_to_cost, current_tier_refund, label) are filled in by this tool. upgrade_to_subclass on a ride `remove` marks a tier upgrade and gates the remove on the replacement being affordable in time. Example: [{\"action\":\"place\",\"type\":\"ride\",\"subtype\":\"carousel\",\"subclass\":\"yellow\",\"price\":4}]"
                        }
                    },
                    required = ["cash", "step", "horizon", "recurring_daily", "placed_shops", "placed_rides", "proposals"]
                }
            }
        },

        {
            name = "ActiveTrials",
            class = "coded_tools.maps_park.active_trials.ActiveTrials",
            function = {
                description = "Return the active trials joined across trial_strategies (rule body) and trial_strategies_criteria (metadata), optionally filtered to one domain. Pass domain=<your domain> to get just your trials. Returns {domain, count, trials:[{trial_id, rule, domain, section, edit_type, find_text, step_start, ep, success_criterion, failure_criterion, rationale}]}.",
                parameters = {
                    type = "object",
                    properties = {
                        domain = { type = "string", description = "Filter to one domain (rides/shops/staff/research/layout/director/coordinator). Omit for all active trials." }
                    }
                }
            }
        },

        {
            name = "RecurringDaily",
            class = "coded_tools.maps_park.recurring_daily.RecurringDaily",
            function = {
                description = "Compute the integer recurring_daily cost (staff salaries + research speed_cost) used by FinanceGate. Replaces LLM-side arithmetic — reads salaries from economics_staff and speed_cost from economics_research and sums them. Returns {recurring_daily, staff_breakdown, staff_subtotal, research_speed, research_speed_cost}.",
                parameters = {
                    type = "object",
                    properties = {
                        placed_staff = {
                            type = "array",
                            items = { type = "object" },
                            description = "Pass status.placed_staff verbatim — list of objects each with at least {subtype, subclass}."
                        }
                        research_speed = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "Pass status.research_speed verbatim. One of: none, slow, medium, fast."
                        }
                    },
                    required = ["placed_staff", "research_speed"]
                }
            }
        },

        {
            name = "state_read",
            class = "coded_tools.file_management.state_read.StateRead",
            function = {
                description = "Read a file by its logical name from the operator-configured name_map.",
                parameters = {
                    type = "object",
                    properties = {
                        name = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "Logical name from the operator-configured name_map."
                        }
                    },
                    required = ["name"]
                }
            },
            args = {
                name_map = {
                    # State files (mutable runtime)
                    # user_directives is operator-owned (runner --user-strategy); read-only
                    # to agents (intentionally NOT in the state_write name_map) so it is
                    # never falsified or edited by the network.
                    user_directives      = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/user_directives.md"
                    trial_strategies     = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/trial_strategies.md"
                    trial_strategies_outcome = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/trial_strategies_outcome.md"
                    trial_strategies_criteria = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/trial_strategies_criteria.md"
                    last_reward          = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/last_reward.md"
                    playbook_director    = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_director.md"
                    playbook_coordinator = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_coordinator.md"
                    playbook_rides       = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_rides.md"
                    playbook_shops       = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_shops.md"
                    playbook_staff       = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_staff.md"
                    playbook_research    = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_research.md"
                    playbook_layout      = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_layout.md"
                    # Read-only economics references (numeric tables)
                    economics_rides      = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/rides_economics.md"
                    economics_shops      = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/shops_economics.md"
                    economics_staff      = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/staff_economics.md"
                    economics_research   = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/research_economics.md"
                    world_constants      = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/world_constants.md"
                    # Seed sources (consumed once on episode 1 by curator.seed and memory_keeper)
                    seed_playbook_director    = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/director_strategy.md"
                    seed_playbook_coordinator = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/coordinator_strategy.md"
                    seed_playbook_rides       = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/rides_strategy.md"
                    seed_playbook_shops       = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/shops_strategy.md"
                    seed_playbook_staff       = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/staff_strategy.md"
                    seed_playbook_research    = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/research_strategy.md"
                    seed_playbook_layout      = "coded_tools/maps_park/config_files/world_strategy.md"
                }
            }
        },

        {
            name = "state_write",
            class = "coded_tools.file_management.state_write.StateWrite",
            function = {
                description = "Write content to a state file by its logical NAME. mode='overwrite' (default) replaces the body; mode='append' appends. Writable names: trial_strategies, trial_strategies_criteria, trial_strategies_outcome, playbook_<domain>. last_reward is NOT writable here — it is managed exclusively by the advance_episode Python tool at episode end. Seed and economics names are also not writable.",
                parameters = {
                    type = "object",
                    properties = {
                        name = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "Logical state name from the operator-configured name_map."
                        },
                        content = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "Text body to write."
                        },
                        mode = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "'overwrite' (default) or 'append'."
                        }
                    },
                    required = ["name", "content"]
                }
            },
            args = {
                # last_reward is intentionally OMITTED here. It is written
                # only by the advance_episode Python coded tool (at episode
                # end). Agents can read it via state_read but must not write
                # to it — earlier mis-writes corrupted the file with
                # turn-shaped data while episodes were still in progress.
                name_map = {
                    trial_strategies     = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/trial_strategies.md"
                    trial_strategies_outcome = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/trial_strategies_outcome.md"
                    trial_strategies_criteria = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/trial_strategies_criteria.md"
                    playbook_director    = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_director.md"
                    playbook_coordinator = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_coordinator.md"
                    playbook_rides       = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_rides.md"
                    playbook_shops       = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_shops.md"
                    playbook_staff       = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_staff.md"
                    playbook_research    = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_research.md"
                    playbook_layout      = "coded_tools/maps_park/state/playbook_layout.md"
                }
            }
        },

        {
            name = "ProposeAction",
            class = "coded_tools.maps_park.propose_action.ProposeAction",
            function = {
                description = "Propose ONE MAPs action without committing to the simulator. Runs cheap deterministic validation (action-name, price-cap, place-bounds, basic cash check) and persists the proposal to coded_tools/maps_park/state/proposed_action.json so the external runner can read it. Returns {proposed:{park,action,args}, validation:{ok,reasons}}. The runner is the single source of truth for actually stepping the env; if validation.ok=false, the runner will re-prompt with the rejection reasons. Same argument shape as ActionDispatcher.",
                parameters = {
                    type = "object",
                    properties = {
                        park = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "Always '0'."
                        },
                        action = {
                            type = "string",
                            description = "One of: wait, place, move, remove, modify, set_research, survey_guests."
                        },
                        args = {
                            type = "object",
                            description = "All numeric values as quoted strings. Same key layout per action as ActionDispatcher."
                        }
                    },
                    required = ["park", "action", "args"]
                }
            }
        }
    ]
}
